the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert Belet was born about 1290. She had at least 2 sons with Robert Belet."},"et":{"about 1290–":"umbes 1290–Surnud","1295–1323":"1295–1323","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1323":"1323","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","about 1322":"1322","estimated 1320":"umbes 1320","1290":"1290","Bellot, Norfolk,, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1290–":"noin 1290–Kuollut","1295–1323":"1295–1323","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1322–Male":"1322–Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1323":"1323","about 1290":"noin 1290","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","about 1322":"1322","estimated 1320":"noin 1320","1290":"1290","Bellot, Norfolk,, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1290–":"environ 1290–Décédée","1295–1323":"1295–1323","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1322–Male":"1322–Décédé","1290–Female":"1290–Décédée","1323":"1323","about 1290":"environ 1290","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","about 1322":"1322","estimated 1320":"environ 1320","1290":"1290","Bellot, Norfolk,, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert Belet est née